main event: A bright white object was observed in the sky over Lincoln, Nebraska that appeared to be round, bright white in color, and proceeding in a straight line at high frequency, altitude approximately 500 ft.
interesting points: The observer saw the object approximately 700 times in 25 minutes, and it moved very rapidly and erratically, changing direction frequently and disappearing suddenly.
The object progressed from white to orange and grew weaker, gradually fading out over the course of 1-1.5 minutes.
The observer was initially moon watching using binoculars, then observed the object with the naked eye.
Weather conditions included clear skies and gusty surface winds of 10-15 knots, and a Perseid meteor shower was occurring at the time.
The reporting officer believed the observed object to be of astronomical nature, after consulting with a university planetarium expert.
witnesses: a single observer, identified as SSGT William J. Jacobs
photographs: no, there are no photographs present in the document
